         <abstract>
            <title>Abstract</title>
            <p>In the present study 40 buffaloes suffering from various omaso-abomasal disorders were
          subjected to clinical, haematobiochemical and ultrasonographic examination and
          laparorumenotomy. During M-mode ultrasonographic examination, the buffaloes showed no
          motility of omasum or abomasum. The walls of the omasum and abomasum were observed as
          linear hyperechoic structures; and the impacted feed contents were seen as anechoic
          acoustic shadows in both organs. The values of plasma sodium, potassium and chloride
          decreased as compared to control animals. It was concluded that ultrasonography is a
          suitable technique for diagnosis of omasal impaction, abomasal impaction/dilatation and
          omasal impaction associated with diaphragmatic hernia; and hypochloremic and hypokalemic
          metabolic alkalosis is a diagnostic indicator of abomasal impaction and dilatation.</p>
         </abstract>
